;<br>Someone with psychiatric problems may expereience what sounds like a K=
undalini rise, but it may or may not be one.<br> <br>It must be conced=
ed though that Kundalini spontaneously rising through various nadis without=
 one having gone through proper preparation in this life (i.e. fine-tuning =
of one's attitude and development of detachment) CAN create havoc!<br> =
;<br>One may wonder how Kundalini may spontaneously rise in a layman with n=
o sadhana, while many serious sadhakas may not experience it.<br> <br>=
Firstly, Kundalini rise is NOT an achievement. It is just A SMALL STEP in o=
vercoming one's current limited identity.<br> <br>Let me give an analo=
gy. One wanting to move from one's small dilapidated house (this body-mind =
complex) to a huge palace (realized Self) may first construct the palace ov=
er time and
 move into it when it is COMPLETE. Alternately, if one occasion=
ally goes and stays in the palace still under construction (analogy for out=
 of body experiences due to Kundalini rise), is it an achievement? In fact,=
 it comes with risks. The former approach is safer and one loses nothing in=
 it. Similarly, one can progress towards complete Self-realization without =
any out of body experiences. These are not my word's, but Maharshi Vasishth=
a's words to Lord Rama.<br> <br>Secondly, one does not get something w=
ithout wanting it and putting sufficient effort towards it. One may have de=
eply desired a Kundalini rise in a previous life and may have put enough ef=
fort. As a result, one may be getting it now. But one may be unprepared (an=
d ironically may not even want it!) when it comes in this life.<br> <b=
r>As you do sadhana, try not to fancy too many specific desires. Nature has=
 a delay mechanism in granting your desires (because of constraints on what=

 Nature can give you right now, arising from YOUR OWN previous actions). S=
o Nature sometimes gives you what you want LATE, when you no longer want it=
 or want something else. For example, one may pray for great wealth one's w=
hole life and be born as a rich but very sick man in next life. One may not=
 enjoy that wealth and pray whole life for health. In the life after that, =
one may be very healthy, but not have any knowledge or money. </span><span =
id=3D"yiv255306719yui_3_7_2_19_1362067846619_141">In another case, one may =
deeply desire to act in a famous film. One may be reborn as a tiger or a do=
g and act in a famous film, but not really enjoy that experience. Basically=
, people </span><span id=3D"yiv255306719yui_3_7_2_19_1362067846619_141">kee=
p going in circles through various lives, always "seeking" something they a=
re "missing".<br> <br>Anyway, coming back to Kundalini, if one deeply =
desires an out of body experience given by a rising Kundalini and one's
 pr=
evious karmas constrain one from having it in THIS life, one may be born in=
 next life with this specific desire destined to fructify (if there is enou=
gh karmik force behind it).<br> <br>*     &nb=
sp;  *        *<br> <br>Kundal=
ini rise is not necessarily scary or painful, if one is well-prepared in te=
rms of attitude and detachment.<br> <br>Once I saw a chipmunk glued to=
 a mouse trap. I went to free it and it panicked so badly and started to sh=
ake violently. I went to save it from a certain slow death and it was scare=
d that I would kill it!<br> <br>We are like that chipmunk, glued to th=
e mouse trap called this body-mind complex and scared of being rescued from=
 a certain slow death!<br> <br>If our ideas about who we are (viz this=
 current body-mind complex) are incorrect and if we are this "infinite Self=
" as shastras say, won't a complete realization of that at some
 stage invo=
lve stepping out of this body-mind complex, without being scared?<br> =
<br>*        *    &n=
bsp;   *<br> <br>Kundalini rise after most undesirable condi=
tioning is overcome, is far better than Kundalini rise forced when some rea=
lly undesirable conditioning is still left in one's system.<br> <br>Wh=
en one transcends one problematic notion about who one is and what one need=
s, another notion that lay buried deeper in consciousness may spring to the=
 surface and torment one. If one overcomes the notion "I am the body", ther=
e may be another notion in one's body-mind complex that one's awareness cli=
ngs on to (</span><span id=3D"yiv255306719yui_3_7_2_19_1362067846619_141"><=
span class=3D"yiv255306719userContent">e.g. a great doctor, a great leader,=
 a great scholar, a great saint etc</span>). As an extreme example, if one =
person had a hidden deep desire to be a great soul who rescues
 the world, =
he may fancy that he is a re-incarnated X or Y who will rescue the world no=
w. When one's self-awareness (i.e. Kundalini!) deeply clings to any such no=
tion, it can cause havoc. The person may show some signs of progress and ye=
t remain in ignorance and get stuck badly.<br> <br>An awakened Kundali=
ni in a system with undesirable conditioning may accentuate one's weaknesse=
s and wrong notions heavily and cause serious psychiatric and spiritual pro=
blems.<br> <br>*        * &nbs=
p;      *<br> <br id=3D"yiv255306719yui_3_7_2=
_19_1362067846619_158">The best approach I recommend is to NOT think in ter=
ms of Kundalini and its rise. Just do sadhana, overcome your weaknesses and=
 improve your detachment over time. Again, I want to emphasize that detachm=
ent is not disgust or distaste for life/things/people around you. Disgust i=
s the other side of coin of attachment.</span> It is a
 negative attachment=
.  </div>
